Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Observations:</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills. Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork after transferring to the district. Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers. Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work. Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though reading directions are the\nsame every day. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010. Carmela sat with her\nsmall group. Two students sat to her left and one student sat to her\nright. The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na moment. Carmela immediately began reading. \nShe pointed at the words with the finger on her right hand as she\nread. Carmela sat with her right leg crossed over her left\nas she read. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela sat. Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions. Carmela answered\ncorrectly. Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so. Carmela answered the question correctly. \nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela answered the\nquestion. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment. A male student got out of his seat, kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair. \nCarmela watched the student, and then she performed the same\nactions. The other two students also did, and Carmela continued to\nread aloud quietly with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher sat in\na chair in front of the group. Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain. Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her turn to. \nShe followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group. Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away when it was time to. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat. The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared. Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment. Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion. The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did. Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern. \nCarmela smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment. Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span> </p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<span style="text-decoration:underline;"></span></span></p>	<p style="text-align:center;"><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH/LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION REPORT</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Client\nName: Carmela Ruelas</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background\nInformation:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background information\nwas obtained through review of available records. Carmela is a\nkindergarten student at West Point Elementary School. She has previously\nreceived speech-language therapy from Battle Creek Public Schools. The\nrecent evaluation was conducted because Carmela was up for her three year\nreevaluation. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH\nEVALUATION </span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Golman-Fristoe Test of\nArticulation</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"><br /><br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation. The\nassessment addressed sounds in the initial, medial, and final positions of\nwords. Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> \n</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela's vocal quality,\nrate, and fluency are appropriate for her age and gender. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> Language\nStructure: 88 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Portions of the CELF  4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities. \nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF  4: concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes  receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs. Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions. Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms. The <span style="background:#FFFFFF none repeat scroll 0% 0%;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer. </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture. The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword. Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs. Overall Carmela's scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>. <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3) </span><br />\nStandard Score: 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br /></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Overall\nCarmela's language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children. Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation. In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing. Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school. It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team. <b> </b><br /><br /><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Determination Statement: </span></b> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">Carmela does not meet the <span style="color:#000000;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith Developmental Delay (DD). Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span> </p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<span style="text-decoration:underline;"></span></span></p>\n\n\n<span style="font-size:10pt;"></span>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> Language\nStructure: 88 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Portions of the CELF  4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities. \nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF  4: concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes  receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs. Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions. Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms. The <span style="background:#FFFFFF none repeat scroll 0% 0%;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer. </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture. The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword. Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs. Overall Carmela's scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>. <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3) </span><br />\nStandard Score: 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br /></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Overall\nCarmela's language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children. Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation. In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing. Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school. It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team. <b> </b><br /><br /><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Determination Statement: </span></b> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">Carmela does not meet the <span style="color:#000000;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith Developmental Delay (DD). Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Observations:</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills. Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork after transferring to the district. Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers. Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work. Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though reading directions are the\nsame every day. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010. Carmela sat with her\nsmall group. Two students sat to her left and one student sat to her\nright. The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na moment. Carmela immediately began reading. \nShe pointed at the words with the finger on her right hand as she\nread. Carmela sat with her right leg crossed over her left\nas she read. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela sat. Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions. Carmela answered\ncorrectly. Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so. Carmela answered the question correctly. \nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela answered the\nquestion. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment. A male student got out of his seat, kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair. \nCarmela watched the student, and then she performed the same\nactions. The other two students also did, and Carmela continued to\nread aloud quietly with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher sat in\na chair in front of the group. Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain. Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her turn to. \nShe followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group. Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away when it was time to. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat. The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared. Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment. Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion. The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did. Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern. \nCarmela smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment. Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span> </p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<span style="text-decoration:underline;"></span></span></p>	2011-02-15	<p style="text-align:center;"><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH/LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION REPORT</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Client\nName: Carmela Ruelas</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background\nInformation:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background information\nwas obtained through review of available records. Carmela is a\nkindergarten student at West Point Elementary School. She has previously\nreceived speech-language therapy from Battle Creek Public Schools. The\nrecent evaluation was conducted because Carmela was up for her three year\nreevaluation. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH\nEVALUATION </span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Golman-Fristoe Test of\nArticulation</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"><br /><br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation. Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her turn to. \nShe followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group. Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away when it was time to. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat. The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared. Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment. Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion. The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did. Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern. \nCarmela smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment. Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span> </p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<span style="text-decoration:underline;"></span></span></p>	2011-02-25	<p style="text-align:center;"><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH/LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION REPORT</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Client\nName: Carmela Ruelas</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background\nInformation:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background information\nwas obtained through review of available records. Carmela is a\nkindergarten student at West Point Elementary School. She has previously\nreceived speech-language therapy from Battle Creek Public Schools. The\nrecent evaluation was conducted because Carmela was up for her three year\nreevaluation. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH\nEVALUATION </span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Golman-Fristoe Test of\nArticulation</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"><br /><br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation. The\nassessment addressed sounds in the initial, medial, and final positions of\nwords. Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> \n</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela's vocal quality,\nrate, and fluency are appropriate for her age and gender. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> Language\nStructure: 88 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Portions of the CELF  4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities. \nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF  4: concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes  receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs. Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions. Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms. The <span style="background:#FFFFFF none repeat scroll 0% 0%;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer. </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture. The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword. Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs. Overall Carmela's scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>. <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3) </span><br />\nStandard Score: 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br /></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Overall\nCarmela's language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children. Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation. In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing. Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school. It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team. <b> </b><br /><br /><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Determination Statement: </span></b> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">Carmela does not meet the <span style="color:#000000;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith Developmental Delay (DD). Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Observations:</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills. Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork after transferring to the district. Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers. Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work. Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though reading directions are the\nsame every day. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010. Carmela sat with her\nsmall group. Two students sat to her left and one student sat to her\nright. The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na moment. Carmela immediately began reading. \nShe pointed at the words with the finger on her right hand as she\nread. Carmela sat with her right leg crossed over her left\nas she read. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela sat. Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions. Carmela answered\ncorrectly. Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so. Carmela answered the question correctly. \nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela answered the\nquestion. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment. A male student got out of his seat, kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair. \nCarmela watched the student, and then she performed the same\nactions. The other two students also did, and Carmela continued to\nread aloud quietly with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher sat in\na chair in front of the group. Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain. Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Observations:</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills. Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork after transferring to the district. Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers. Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work. Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though reading directions are the\nsame every day. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010. Carmela sat with her\nsmall group. Two students sat to her left and one student sat to her\nright. The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na moment. Carmela immediately began reading. \nShe pointed at the words with the finger on her right hand as she\nread. Carmela sat with her right leg crossed over her left\nas she read. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela sat. Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions. Carmela answered\ncorrectly. Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so. Carmela answered the question correctly. \nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela answered the\nquestion. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment. A male student got out of his seat, kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair. \nCarmela watched the student, and then she performed the same\nactions. The other two students also did, and Carmela continued to\nread aloud quietly with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher sat in\na chair in front of the group. Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain. Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her turn to. \nShe followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group. Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away when it was time to. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat. The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared. Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment. Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion. The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did. Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern. \nCarmela smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment. Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span> </p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<span style="text-decoration:underline;"></span></span></p>	2011-02-09	<p style="text-align:center;"><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH/LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION REPORT</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Client\nName: Carmela Ruelas</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background\nInformation:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Background information\nwas obtained through review of available records. Carmela is a\nkindergarten student at West Point Elementary School. She has previously\nreceived speech-language therapy from Battle Creek Public Schools. The\nrecent evaluation was conducted because Carmela was up for her three year\nreevaluation. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH\nEVALUATION </span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Golman-Fristoe Test of\nArticulation</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"><br /><br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation. The\nassessment addressed sounds in the initial, medial, and final positions of\nwords. Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> \n</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela's vocal quality,\nrate, and fluency are appropriate for her age and gender. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> Language\nStructure: 88 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Portions of the CELF  4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities. \nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF  4: concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes  receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs. Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions. Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms. The <span style="background:#FFFFFF none repeat scroll 0% 0%;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer. </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture. The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword. Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs. Overall Carmela's scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>. <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3) </span><br />\nStandard Score: 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br /></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Overall\nCarmela's language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children. Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation. In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing. Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school. It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team. <b> </b><br /><br /><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Determination Statement: </span></b> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">Carmela does not meet the <span style="color:#000000;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith Developmental Delay (DD). The\nrecent evaluation was conducted because Carmela was up for her three year\nreevaluation. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">SPEECH\nEVALUATION </span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Golman-Fristoe Test of\nArticulation</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"><br /><br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation. Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> \n</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela's vocal quality,\nrate, and fluency are appropriate for her age and gender. </span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;"><span style="font-size:10pt;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> Language\nStructure: 88 </span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;"> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Portions of the CELF  4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities. \nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF  4: concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes  receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs. Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions. Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms. The <span style="background:#FFFFFF none repeat scroll 0% 0%;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer. </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture. The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword. Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs. Overall Carmela's scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>. <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3) </span><br />\nStandard Score: 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p><b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br /></span></b><span style="font-size:10pt;">Overall\nCarmela's language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children. Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation. In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing. Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school. It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team. <b> </b><br /><br /><b><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Determination Statement: </span></b> </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">Carmela does not meet the <span style="color:#000000;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith Developmental Delay (DD). Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development, </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;"> <span style="text-decoration:underline;">Observations:</span></span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills. Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork after transferring to the district. Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers. Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work. Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though reading directions are the\nsame every day. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010. Carmela sat with her\nsmall group. Two students sat to her left and one student sat to her\nright. The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na moment. Carmela immediately began reading. \nShe pointed at the words with the finger on her right hand as she\nread. Carmela sat with her right leg crossed over her left\nas she read. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela sat. Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions. Carmela answered\ncorrectly. Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so. Carmela answered the question correctly. \nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela answered the\nquestion. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment. A male student got out of his seat, kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair. \nCarmela watched the student, and then she performed the same\nactions. The other two students also did, and Carmela continued to\nread aloud quietly with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">The teacher sat in\na chair in front of the group. Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain. Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her turn to. \nShe followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group. Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away when it was time to. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat. The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did. Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern. \nCarmela smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment. Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation. </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span> </p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or </span></p>\n\n<p><span style="font-size:10pt;font-family:Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<span style="text-decoration:underline;"></span></span></p>	2011-02-16	2011-02-16	2011-02-21	\N	\N	2011-02-27	f	\N	2005-10-11	12	2011-02-24	\N	Albanian	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	None	9	\N	\N	2011-02-09 17:41:00	1000254	Agency Name

Achievement Test\r\n third edition. This instrument measured her academic skills in a wide \r\nrange of areas. Haley worked hard during the testing session and \r\nappeared to put forth her best effort on all items. She needed \r\nencouragement to attempt items that were difficult, but would attempt \r\nthem most of the time with verbal prompting. The following results \r\nshould be considered an accurate estimate of her current educational \r\nabilities as compared to her same age peers. <br />Haley's reading skills \r\nwere measured in 4 different categories, early reading skills, basic \r\nreading skills, reading comprehension and oral reading fluency. The \r\nearly reading skills measured Haley's knowledge of letter names, letter \r\nsounds, rhyming words, and beginning, middle and ending sounds. Haley \r\nrecognizes letters and letter sounds. She is also able to identify \r\nrhyming words and beginning sounds. She struggles to identify beginning \r\nblends and ending sounds in words. She was also able to blend segmented \r\nsounds together to make a word. She scored a standard score of 90. This \r\nis within the average range as compared to same age peers.<br />The word \r\nreading and pseudoword reading subtests are combined to get a standard \r\nscore for reading basic skills. Haley was able to read 2 letter words \r\nand cvc words. She struggled with words that contained blends and were \r\nmulti-syllable. She scored a standard score of 77. This is within the \r\nbelow average range as compared to same age peers. <br />The reading \r\ncomprehension subtest measures how well Haley is able to answer \r\nquestions over a passage that she has read independently. Haley \r\nstruggled to read the passages, but would go back and attempt to reread \r\nto find information after a question was asked of her. She struggled to \r\nanswer inference questions and was inconsistent on basic factual recall \r\nquestions. She scored a standard score of 77. This is within the below \r\naverage range as compared to same age peers.<br />The oral reading fluency\r\n subtest measures Haley's fluency, smoothness and pacing when reading. \r\nHaley was asked to read 2 different passages. One passage was narrative \r\ntext and the other was informational text. These grade level passages \r\nwere very difficult for Haley. She scored a standard score of 66. This \r\nis within the below average range as compared to same age peers.<br />On \r\nthe WIAT-III there is not a standard score for written expression until \r\n3rd grade, however 3 of the subtests that comprise written expression \r\nare administered. The first 2 subtests, sentence composition, measure \r\nhow well Haley is able to combine sentences together and formulate \r\nwritten sentences when given a specific word. Both of these tasks were \r\nextremely difficult for Haley. She was not able to accurately complete \r\nany of the items. She scored a standard score of 57 on the sentence \r\ncomposition subtests. This is below average as compared to her same age \r\npeers. The third subtest that is under the written expression umbrella \r\nis spelling. This subtest looked at how well Haley was able spell words \r\nthat are dictated to her. Haley was able to spell 2 and 3 letter words, \r\nbut struggled with sounding out more complex words. She scored a \r\nstandard score of 72 on the spelling subtest. This is within the below \r\naverage range as compared to same age peers.<br />Haley's math skills were\r\n assessed utilizing the math calculations and math reasoning subtests. \r\nThe math calculations subtest is comprised of a variety of addition, \r\nsubtraction, multiplication and division problems. The problems increase\r\n in difficulty as she works through the problems. Haley was able to \r\nsolve basic addition facts trough the 5's. She utilized her fingers to \r\nhelp her solve the problems. She scored a standard score a standard \r\nscore of 65. This is within the below average range as compared to same \r\nage peers. The math reasoning subtest measured skills such as telling \r\ntime, counting money, interpreting a chart or graph, solving word \r\nproblems, and geometry skills. Haley was able to recognize numbers, but \r\nstruggled to order numbers and solve simple 1 step word problems. She \r\nscored a standard score of 50. This is within the below average range as\r\n compared to same age peers.<br />Overall, Haley demonstrates below \r\naverage academic skills. With encouragement she attempts tasks that are \r\ndifficult, but would benefit from small group and 1:1 support in all \r\nacademic areas. </b></p>";s:9:"processed";s:9834:"<span style="font-family: Arial;">\r\n </span><p style="text-align: center;">Educational Evaluation Report<br />\r\nBellevue Public Schools<br />\r\nStudent: Haley Wienk<br />\r\nDOB: 11-5-2001</p>\r\n<b></b><p><b>Evaluation Dates: 12/01/10</b></p><b></b><table border="1" cellspacing="1" dir="ltr" width="590"><tbody><tr><td style="width: 33%; background-color: rgb(192, 192, 192);"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">Math Reasoning</p></td><td style="width: 33%; background-color: rgb(192, 192, 192);"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">Wechsler Individual Achievement Test-3rd Edition</p></td><td style="width: 33%;"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">50</p></td></tr><tr><td style="width: 33%; background-color: rgb(192, 192, 192);"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">Spelling</p></td><td style="width: 33%; background-color: rgb(192, 192, 192);"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">Wechsler Individual Achievement Test-3rd Edition</p></td><td style="width: 33%;"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">72</p></td></tr><tr><td style="width: 33%; background-color: rgb(192, 192, 192);"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">Sentence Composition</p></td><td style="width: 33%; background-color: rgb(192, 192, 192);"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">Wechsler Individual Achievement Test-3rd Edition</p></td><td style="width: 33%;"><sup><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></sup><p style="text-align: center;">57</p></td></tr></tbody></table><sup><b><span style="font-family: Arial;"></span></b></sup><p><b>Educational\r\n Report: Haley was administered the Wechsler Individual Achievement Test\r\n third edition. This instrument measured her academic skills in a wide \r\nrange of areas. Haley worked hard during the testing session and \r\nappeared to put forth her best effort on all items. She needed \r\nencouragement to attempt items that were difficult, but would attempt \r\nthem most of the time with verbal prompting. The following results \r\nshould be considered an accurate estimate of her current educational \r\nabilities as compared to her same age peers. <br />Haley's reading skills \r\nwere measured in 4 different categories, early reading skills, basic \r\nreading skills, reading comprehension and oral reading fluency. The \r\nearly reading skills measured Haley's knowledge of letter names, letter \r\nsounds, rhyming words, and beginning, middle and ending sounds. Haley \r\nrecognizes letters and letter sounds. She is also able to identify \r\nrhyming words and beginning sounds. She struggles to identify beginning \r\nblends and ending sounds in words. She was also able to blend segmented \r\nsounds together to make a word. She scored a standard score of 90. This \r\nis within the average range as compared to same age peers.<br />The word \r\nreading and pseudoword reading subtests are combined to get a standard \r\nscore for reading basic skills. Haley was able to read 2 letter words \r\nand cvc words. She struggled with words that contained blends and were \r\nmulti-syllable. She scored a standard score of 77. This is within the \r\nbelow average range as compared to same age peers. <br />The reading \r\ncomprehension subtest measures how well Haley is able to answer \r\nquestions over a passage that she has read independently. Haley \r\nstruggled to read the passages, but would go back and attempt to reread \r\nto find information after a question was asked of her. She struggled to \r\nanswer inference questions and was inconsistent on basic factual recall \r\nquestions. She scored a standard score of 77. This is within the below \r\naverage range as compared to same age peers.<br />The oral reading fluency\r\n subtest measures Haley's fluency, smoothness and pacing when reading. \r\nHaley was asked to read 2 different passages. One passage was narrative \r\ntext and the other was informational text. These grade level passages \r\nwere very difficult for Haley. She scored a standard score of 66. This \r\nis within the below average range as compared to same age peers.<br />On \r\nthe WIAT-III there is not a standard score for written expression until \r\n3rd grade, however 3 of the subtests that comprise written expression \r\nare administered. The first 2 subtests, sentence composition, measure \r\nhow well Haley is able to combine sentences together and formulate \r\nwritten sentences when given a specific word. Both of these tasks were \r\nextremely difficult for Haley. She was not able to accurately complete \r\nany of the items. She scored a standard score of 57 on the sentence \r\ncomposition subtests. This is below average as compared to her same age \r\npeers. The third subtest that is under the written expression umbrella \r\nis spelling. This subtest looked at how well Haley was able spell words \r\nthat are dictated to her. Haley was able to spell 2 and 3 letter words, \r\nbut struggled with sounding out more complex words. She scored a \r\nstandard score of 72 on the spelling subtest. This is within the below \r\naverage range as compared to same age peers.<br />Haley's math skills were\r\n assessed utilizing the math calculations and math reasoning subtests. \r\nThe math calculations subtest is comprised of a variety of addition, \r\nsubtraction, multiplication and division problems. The problems increase\r\n in difficulty as she works through the problems. Haley was able to \r\nsolve basic addition facts trough the 5's. She utilized her fingers to \r\nhelp her solve the problems. She scored a standard score a standard \r\nscore of 65. This is within the below average range as compared to same \r\nage peers. The math reasoning subtest measured skills such as telling \r\ntime, counting money, interpreting a chart or graph, solving word \r\nproblems, and geometry skills. Haley was able to recognize numbers, but \r\nstruggled to order numbers and solve simple 1 step word problems. She \r\nscored a standard score of 50. This is within the below average range as\r\n compared to same age peers.<br />Overall, Haley demonstrates below \r\naverage academic skills. With encouragement she attempts tasks that are \r\ndifficult, but would benefit from small group and 1:1 support in all \r\nacademic areas. </b></p><b></b>";s:10:"paste_html";s:10122:"<span style="font-family: Arial;">\r\n </span><p style="text-align: center;">Educational Evaluation Report<br />\r\nBellevue Public Schools<br />\r\nStudent: Haley Wienk<br />\r\nDOB: 11-5-2001</p>\r\n<b></b><p><b>Evaluation Dates: 12/01/10</b></p><b></b><table border="1" cellspacing="1" dir="ltr" width="590"><tbody><tr><td style="width: 33%; 4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities.&nbsp;\nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF &ndash; 4:&nbsp; concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes &ndash; receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs.&nbsp; Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions.&nbsp; Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms.&nbsp; The <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% white;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer.&nbsp; </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture.&nbsp; The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword.&nbsp; Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs.&nbsp; Overall Carmela&rsquo;s scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>.&nbsp; &nbsp;<u>Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </u><br />\nStandard Score:&nbsp; 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation.&nbsp; In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing.&nbsp; font-family: Times;">Carmela&nbsp;does not meet the <span style="color: black;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith&nbsp;Developmental Delay (DD).&nbsp; Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork&nbsp;after transferring to the district.&nbsp; Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives&nbsp;a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work.&nbsp; Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though&nbsp;reading directions are the\nsame every day.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na&nbsp;moment.&nbsp; Carmela&nbsp;immediately&nbsp;began reading.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;pointed at the words&nbsp;with the finger on her right hand as she\nread.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her&nbsp;right&nbsp;leg crossed over&nbsp;her left\nas she read.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela&nbsp;sat.&nbsp; Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions.&nbsp; Carmela answered\ncorrectly.&nbsp; Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so.&nbsp; Carmela answered the question correctly.&nbsp;\nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela&nbsp;answered the\nquestion.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment.&nbsp; A male student got out of his seat,&nbsp;kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair.&nbsp;\nCarmela watched the student, and&nbsp;then she performed the same\nactions.&nbsp; The other two students also did, and&nbsp;Carmela continued to\nread&nbsp;aloud quietly&nbsp;with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher&nbsp;sat in\na chair in front of the group.&nbsp; Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions&nbsp;for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain.&nbsp; Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her&nbsp;turn to.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group.&nbsp; Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away&nbsp;when it was time to.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat.&nbsp; The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared.&nbsp; Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment.&nbsp; Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion.&nbsp; The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did.&nbsp; Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern.&nbsp;\nCarmela&nbsp;smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment.&nbsp; Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork&nbsp;after transferring to the district.&nbsp; Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives&nbsp;a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work.&nbsp; Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though&nbsp;reading directions are the\nsame every day.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her\nsmall group.&nbsp; Two students sat&nbsp;to her left and one student sat to her\nright.&nbsp; The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na&nbsp;moment.&nbsp; Carmela&nbsp;immediately&nbsp;began reading.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;pointed at the words&nbsp;with the finger on her right hand as she\nread.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her&nbsp;right&nbsp;leg crossed over&nbsp;her left\nas she read.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela&nbsp;sat.&nbsp; Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions.&nbsp; Carmela answered\ncorrectly.&nbsp; Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so.&nbsp; Carmela answered the question correctly.&nbsp;\nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela&nbsp;answered the\nquestion.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment.&nbsp; A male student got out of his seat,&nbsp;kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair.&nbsp;\nCarmela watched the student, and&nbsp;then she performed the same\nactions.&nbsp; The other two students also did, and&nbsp;Carmela continued to\nread&nbsp;aloud quietly&nbsp;with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher&nbsp;sat in\na chair in front of the group.&nbsp; Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions&nbsp;for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain.&nbsp; Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her&nbsp;turn to.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group.&nbsp; Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away&nbsp;when it was time to.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat.&nbsp; The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared.&nbsp; Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment.&nbsp; Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion.&nbsp; The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did.&nbsp; Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern.&nbsp;\nCarmela&nbsp;smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment.&nbsp; Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<u></u></span></p>\n\n\n	\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n<style>@font-face {\n  font-family: &quot;Times&quot;;\n}@font-face {\n  font-family: &quot;&#65325;&#65331;
