font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Client\nName:&nbsp; Carmela Ruelas</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Background\nInformation:</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Background information\nwas obtained through review of available records.&nbsp; Carmela is a\nkindergarten student at West Point Elementary School.&nbsp; She has previously\nreceived speech-language therapy from Battle Creek Public Schools.&nbsp; The\nrecent evaluation was conducted because Carmela was up for her three year\nreevaluation.&nbsp; &nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><u><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">SPEECH\nEVALUATION </span></u></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Golman-Fristoe Test of\nArticulation</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"><br />\n<br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation.&nbsp; The\nassessment addressed sounds in the initial, medial, and final positions of\nwords.&nbsp; Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110.&nbsp; </span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;\n</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela&rsquo;s vocal quality,\nrate, and fluency are appropriate for her age and gender.&nbsp; </span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><u><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></u></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81&nbsp; </span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;Language\nStructure: 88&nbsp;</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;<b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Portions of the CELF &ndash; 4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities.&nbsp;\nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF &ndash; 4:&nbsp; concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes &ndash; receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs.&nbsp; Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions.&nbsp; Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms.&nbsp; The <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% white;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer.&nbsp; </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture.&nbsp; The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword.&nbsp; Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs.&nbsp; Overall Carmela&rsquo;s scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>.&nbsp; &nbsp;<u>Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </u><br />\nStandard Score:&nbsp; 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br />\n</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Overall\nCarmela&rsquo;s language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children.&nbsp; Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation.&nbsp; In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing.&nbsp; Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school.&nbsp; It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team.&nbsp;<b>&nbsp;</b><br />\n<br />\n<b><u>Determination Statement:&nbsp;&nbsp;</u></b>&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Times;">Carmela&nbsp;does not meet the <span style="color: black;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith&nbsp;Developmental Delay (DD).&nbsp; Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation.&nbsp; In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing.&nbsp; Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school.&nbsp; It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team.&nbsp;<b>&nbsp;</b><br />\n<br />\n<b><u>Determination Statement:&nbsp;&nbsp;</u></b>&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Times;">Carmela&nbsp;does not meet the <span style="color: black;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith&nbsp;Developmental Delay (DD).&nbsp; Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;<u>Observations:</u></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills.&nbsp; Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork&nbsp;after transferring to the district.&nbsp; Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives&nbsp;a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work.&nbsp; Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though&nbsp;reading directions are the\nsame every day.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her\nsmall group.&nbsp; Two students sat&nbsp;to her left and one student sat to her\nright.&nbsp; The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na&nbsp;moment.&nbsp; Carmela&nbsp;immediately&nbsp;began reading.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;pointed at the words&nbsp;with the finger on her right hand as she\nread.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her&nbsp;right&nbsp;leg crossed over&nbsp;her left\nas she read.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela&nbsp;sat.&nbsp; Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions.&nbsp; Carmela answered\ncorrectly.&nbsp; Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so.&nbsp; Carmela answered the question correctly.&nbsp;\nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela&nbsp;answered the\nquestion.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment.&nbsp; A male student got out of his seat,&nbsp;kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair.&nbsp;\nCarmela watched the student, and&nbsp;then she performed the same\nactions.&nbsp; The other two students also did, and&nbsp;Carmela continued to\nread&nbsp;aloud quietly&nbsp;with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher&nbsp;sat in\na chair in front of the group.&nbsp; Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions&nbsp;for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain.&nbsp; Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her&nbsp;turn to.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group.&nbsp; Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away&nbsp;when it was time to.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat.&nbsp; The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared.&nbsp; Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment.&nbsp; Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion.&nbsp; The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did.&nbsp; Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern.&nbsp;\nCarmela&nbsp;smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment.&nbsp; Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"><br />\n<br />\nCarmela was administered the Goldman-Fristoe Test of Articulation.&nbsp; The\nassessment addressed sounds in the initial, medial, and final positions of\nwords.&nbsp; Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110.&nbsp; </span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; </span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><u><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></u></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;<b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Portions of the CELF &ndash; 4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities.&nbsp;\nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF &ndash; 4:&nbsp; concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes &ndash; receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs.&nbsp; Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions.&nbsp; Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms.&nbsp; The <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% white;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer.&nbsp; </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture.&nbsp; The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword.&nbsp; Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs.&nbsp; Overall Carmela&rsquo;s scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>.&nbsp; &nbsp;<u>Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </u><br />\nStandard Score:&nbsp; 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation.&nbsp; In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing.&nbsp; Carmela made no articulation errors during this assessment and\nreceived a standard score of 110.&nbsp; </span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Vocal\nQuality/Rate/Fluency:</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;\n</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela&rsquo;s vocal quality,\nrate, and fluency are appropriate for her age and gender.&nbsp; </span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><u><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">LANGUAGE\nEVALUATION</span></u></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Clinical\nEvaluation of Language Fundamentals - 4 (CELF-4)</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Core\nLanguage Standard Score: 81&nbsp; </span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Receptive\nLanguage: 86</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Expressive\nLanguage: 89</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Language\nContent: 84</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;"></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;Language\nStructure: 88&nbsp;</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;<b>CELF\nSummary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Portions of the CELF &ndash; 4\nwere administered to Carmela in order to examine her language abilities.&nbsp;\nCarmela was given the following subtests of the CELF &ndash; 4:&nbsp; concepts and\nfollowing directions, word structure, recalling sentences, formulated\nsentences, word classes &ndash; receptive and expressive, sentence structure,\nexpressive vocabulary, and understanding spoken paragraphs.&nbsp; Concepts and\nfollowing directions require the examinee to listen to multistep directions, and\nthe examinee is to follow those directions.&nbsp; Word structure stimulus items\nconsist of the examinee demonstrating proper use of pronouns and noun and verb\nforms.&nbsp; The <span style="background: none repeat scroll 0% 0% white;">recalling sentences subtest\nrequires the examinee to repeat sentences that are presented by the\nexaminer.&nbsp; </span>The formulated sentences subtest consists of stimulus\nitems that contain a target word and a picture.&nbsp; The examinee is\ninstructed to produce a sentence that depicts the picture using the target\nword.&nbsp; Understanding spoken paragraphs consists of the examinee answering\nquestions in regard to three paragraphs.&nbsp; Overall Carmela&rsquo;s scores fell\nwithin the average range when compared to same age peers<b>.&nbsp; &nbsp;<u>Peabody\nPicture Vocabulary Test -3 (PPVT-3)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </u><br />\nStandard Score:&nbsp; 94<br />\nPPVT Summary of Findings:</b></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Summary and\nRecommendations:<br />\n</span></b><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Overall\nCarmela&rsquo;s language scores fell in the average to low average range when\ncompared to same aged children.&nbsp; Carmela does not meet Nebraska Department\nof Education Rule 51 written criteria to be verified as a student having\nspeech-language impairment in the area of language or articulation.&nbsp; In\norder to help Carmela increase her vocabulary skills, while driving in the car\ntalk about what she is seeing.&nbsp; Have her recall three things that she\ndiscussed during her day at school.&nbsp; It is recommended that these results\nbe reviewed by the multidisciplinary team.&nbsp;<b>&nbsp;</b><br />\n<br />\n<b><u>Determination Statement:&nbsp;&nbsp;</u></b>&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Times;">Carmela&nbsp;does not meet the <span style="color: black;">Nebraska\nDepartment of Education Rule 51, Regulations and Standards for Special\nEducation Programs, </span>criteria for verification as a student\nwith&nbsp;Developmental Delay (DD).&nbsp; Information to determine this\nverification was collected through the Adaptive Behavior Assessment System,\nSecond Edition (ABAS-II); parent and teacher interviews; review of school\nrecords; and observations.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">To qualify for special\neducation services in the category of developmental delay, the child shall have\na significant delay as measured by appropriate diagnostic instruments and\nprocedures in one or more of the following areas and, by reason thereof needs\nspecial education and related services:006.04E1a Cognitive development,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1b Physical\ndevelopment,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1c Communication\ndevelopment,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1d Social or\nemotional development,&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1e Adaptive\nbehavior or skills development, or&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E1f A diagnosed\nphysical or medical condition that has a high probability of resulting in a\nsubstantial delay in function in one or more of such areas.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E2\nDevelopmental delay must be considered as one possible eligibility category for\ninfants and toddlers birth through age four, and is a discretionary option for\nschool districts and approved cooperatives to use for children age five through\neight.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">&nbsp;<u>Observations:</u></span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Mrs. Hatterman noted\nthat Carmela has good social skills.&nbsp; Mrs. Hatterman also reported that\nCarmela does well academically, and that she caught on quickly to academic\nwork&nbsp;after transferring to the district.&nbsp; Carmela does show a need\nwith keeping on task when working on papers.&nbsp;&nbsp;Carmela is often\noff-task with paperwork until she receives&nbsp;a direct prompt to start\nworking, but then she is able to complete the work.&nbsp; Understanding\ndirections may be a factor for Carmela, though&nbsp;reading directions are the\nsame every day.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was observed\nduring her morning Reading class on January 5, 2010.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her\nsmall group.&nbsp; Two students sat&nbsp;to her left and one student sat to her\nright.&nbsp; The teacher asked the group to read on their own for\na&nbsp;moment.&nbsp; Carmela&nbsp;immediately&nbsp;began reading.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;pointed at the words&nbsp;with the finger on her right hand as she\nread.&nbsp; Carmela sat with her&nbsp;right&nbsp;leg crossed over&nbsp;her left\nas she read.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stood behind\nthe group and to the left of where Carmela&nbsp;sat.&nbsp; Carmela looked back\nat the teacher when the teacher asked questions.&nbsp; Carmela answered\ncorrectly.&nbsp; Carmela turned the page right away upon the teacher's prompt\nto the group to do so.&nbsp; Carmela answered the question correctly.&nbsp;\nCarmela looked back at the teacher after Carmela&nbsp;answered the\nquestion.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher stepped\naside for a moment.&nbsp; A male student got out of his seat,&nbsp;kneeled in\nfront of his chair, and put his textbook on the seat of his chair.&nbsp;\nCarmela watched the student, and&nbsp;then she performed the same\nactions.&nbsp; The other two students also did, and&nbsp;Carmela continued to\nread&nbsp;aloud quietly&nbsp;with her peers.</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">The teacher&nbsp;sat in\na chair in front of the group.&nbsp; Carmela redirected immediately upon the\nteacher's instructions&nbsp;for the students to sit in their chairs,\nagain.&nbsp; Carmela read aloud correctly when it was her&nbsp;turn to.&nbsp;\nShe&nbsp;followed along with her finger in the textbook when the other students\nread to the group.&nbsp; Carmela got in line with the others students and\nappropriately put her book away&nbsp;when it was time to.&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">Carmela was ready with\nher clipboard and pencil after she returned to her seat.&nbsp; The teacher\ncomplimented Carmela for being prepared.&nbsp; Carmela acknowledged the\ncompliment.&nbsp; Carmela looked at the teacher when the teacher began a\ndiscussion.&nbsp; The teacher instructed the group to turn the page back, and\nCarmela did.&nbsp; Carmela watched the interaction when the teacher and a\nstudent from the group stepped aside to address a concern.&nbsp;\nCarmela&nbsp;smiled at the student sitting next to her when he made a\ncomment.&nbsp; Carmela was on task and her behavior was appropriate throughout\nthe observation.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E3 A child remains\neligible for services under the category of developmental delay:</span>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal" style=""><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: &quot;Times New Roman&quot;;">006.04E3a Through the\nschool year in which the child reaches age five; or&nbsp;</span></p>\n\n<p class="MsoNormal"><span style="font-size: 10pt; font-family: Times;">006.04E3b Through the school year in which the child reaches\nage nine, if the district uses the discretionary option in 92 NAC 51-006.04E2.<u></u></span></p>\n\n\n	\N	23	m	1	w	\N	Individual	1	\N	Home	2011-02-01	2011-03-03	Early Development Network	\N	Other	asdf	\N	\N
